"""
================================================================================
BVAR GDP GROWTH FORECASTING -- Minnesota prior, quarterly, plug-and-play
================================================================================
Bayesian VAR for forecasting US real GDP growth from a daily "as-known"
(point-in-time, forward-filled) Excel panel, resampled to quarter-end.

Methodology (with citations):
  * Minnesota prior implemented via dummy observations:
        Litterman (1986); Doan, Litterman & Sims (1984);
        Banbura, Giannone & Reichlin (2010, JAE) -- "large BVAR" construction.
    Own-lag prior mean delta_i (1 = random walk for persistent levels,
    0 = white noise for growth rates / differenced data), overall tightness
    lambda, harmonic lag decay l^d, scale sigma_i from univariate AR
    residual standard deviations.
  * Sum-of-coefficients ("no-cointegration") prior and dummy-initial-
    observation ("co-persistence") prior: Doan et al. (1984); Sims (1993);
    Sims & Zha (1998).
  * Hyperparameter selection by maximizing the marginal likelihood
    (closed form under the conjugate Normal-Inverse-Wishart):
        Giannone, Lenza & Primiceri (2015, REStat).
  * Conjugate NIW posterior -> exact Monte Carlo (no MCMC needed):
        Sigma ~ IW, B | Sigma ~ Matrix-Normal; density forecasts include
        both parameter and shock uncertainty (Karlsson 2013, Handbook ch.).
  * COVID outliers handled with observation dummies (loose prior), in the
    spirit of Lenza & Primiceri (2022, JAE): extreme pandemic observations
    should not distort the transmission coefficients.
  * Out-of-sample evaluation: recursive (expanding window) pseudo-real-time
    backtest vs. AR(4) and historical-mean benchmarks; RMSE ratios and
    interval coverage.

USAGE
-----
1) Edit CONFIG (file path, columns, transforms).
2) python bvar_gdp.py            (your data)
   python bvar_gdp.py --selftest (synthetic daily panel with known structure)
Outputs (fan chart PNG, OOS PNG, CSVs, summary) -> CONFIG["output_dir"].

EXPECTED DATA LAYOUT
--------------------
One date column (daily), one column per series. Daily rows where each
series holds its latest released value ("dragged down"). The script
resamples to quarter-end ("QE") taking the last known value per quarter
(config per column: "last" or "mean").

IMPORTANT -- TARGET ALIGNMENT: the GDP column in a dragged panel shows the
latest *published* GDP at each date, which references a PREVIOUS quarter.
Set "target_release_shift_q" to realign it to its reference quarter
(typically 1 if your dragged GDP updates with the advance estimate).
See the accompanying notes.
================================================================================
"""

